## The Editorial Process

Every tool page on this site goes through the same workflow before it ships:

**1. Primary source research**
We pull pricing, feature claims, company information, and launch dates from each tool's official site, changelog, and API documentation — not from third-party blog posts or summaries.

**2. Hands-on evaluation**
Where practical, editors test tools on real work — not marketing demos. Where a tool is enterprise-only, B2B-gated, or prohibitively expensive, we note that limitation in the review rather than faking direct experience.

**3. Four-dimension scoring**
Each tool gets scored on Utility, Value, Moat, and Longevity. Scores are deliberate, comparative, and non-inflated. See our full [scoring methodology](/about/scoring/).

**4. Cross-referencing**
Every claim that could become outdated — pricing, context windows, feature availability — is dated. We cite the source and the verification date on every tool page.

**5. Monthly re-verification**
Every page carries a `Verified` timestamp. Our team re-checks high-traffic tool pages monthly (or sooner when a tool ships a material update, changes pricing, or shuts down).

---

## Editorial Principles

**Evidence over opinion.** No claim without a source. If we can't verify it, we don't publish it.

**Honest, comparative scoring.** We do not award 10s to products that aren't genuinely category-leading, and we do not hide 4s and 5s when a tool is weak on the dimension being measured. See the [scoring methodology](/about/scoring/) for examples.

**No promotional language in reviews.** Even when tools we recommend have affiliate programs, we do not mention commissions, referral bonuses, or partnership perks inside the review. Affiliate relationships are tracked internally and disclosed sitewide in the footer — not inside individual tool pages.

**Failures documented.** Discontinued products and rebrands are archived in our [dead tools](/dead/) section, with cause-of-death attribution where known. This protects readers from chasing tools that no longer exist and provides institutional memory for the AI industry.

**Corrections visible, not buried.** When we get something wrong, the page history reflects it. Correction requests go to the editorial team and are reviewed on merit.

---

## What We Don't Do

- **No paid placements.** No tool has ever paid to be listed, ranked, or featured.
- **No "Editor's Pick" sponsorships.** Our recommendations reflect scoring and hands-on use.
- **No affiliate-influenced rankings.** A tool with a 30% commission gets the same editorial lens as one with no program.
- **No AI-generated filler.** Tool pages are written by editors, not churned out by an LLM. We use AI to assist with research and formatting, never for final copy.
- **No unvetted user reviews.** We don't run a community review section because unverified reviews create a race to the bottom on authenticity.

---

## The Team

aipedia.wiki is published by an independent editorial team with backgrounds spanning software engineering, product management, technical writing, and AI tool evaluation. The team operates without outside editorial influence. No investor, parent company, or platform holds editorial veto power.

Individual editors are not named on tool pages — we operate as a publication, not a personality. Every page carries the **aipedia.wiki Editorial** byline because every page has been reviewed by at least two editors before publishing.

---

## Affiliate Disclosure

Some tools on aipedia.wiki have affiliate programs. When you click a link to a tool's official website and make a purchase, we may earn a commission at no additional cost to you. This is how we fund the editorial work.

Critically: affiliate status does **not** influence scores, ranking order, or written assessments. A tool's affiliate commission is tracked in internal site metadata only — you will never see it mentioned inside a review or comparison.

Per FTC guidelines, this sitewide disclosure notice also appears in the footer of every page.

---

## Corrections & Contact

If a price is wrong, a feature has changed, or a tool has shut down, we want to know. Accuracy is our core promise.

Reach the editorial team at the contact address in the site footer. We read every correction request and update pages when evidence supports the change.

If you believe a score is unfair, tell us why — include what you've used the tool for, what you'd score it, and what you'd compare it against. The scoring methodology is transparent and subject to challenge.

